value: Black basalt, moulded. The sphinx crouches on a rectangular pedestal, with its forepaws extended at the front, and its tail curled over its hind quarters. It wears a semi-circular headdress, a bodice, and a saddle blanket, which falls down onto the base. Underneath there is a large circular hole surrounded by four small holes, with a medium-sized hole to the right.

location: on one long side of the pedestal

summary_title: Decorative Wedgwood in Architecture and Furniture
notes: Cf. between pp. 32-3, pl. 6 a Wedgwood sphinx

Cf. pp. 74-5, lot 72, a pair of gilt-bronze chenets of c. 1710. These are related to the designs (although they are not the same) in the Drawings Cabinet at Stockholm. Other examples were sold by Sotheby's on 24 November, 1978, lot 126; Hotel Drouot on 4 December, 1986, illustrated in the Drouot Year Book 1986-87.
Cf. A sphinx in the Victoria and Albert Museum, Jermyn Street Collection (2389-1901), unmarked, see p. 69, no. C34.

Cf. A  pair of sphinxes on rectangular pedestals, traditionally thought to come from Woodhall Park, Hertfordshire,  lot 86, described as George III. L. 162.5 cm. (64 in); height 168 cm (66 in); depth 79 cm (31 in). The text mentions the related sphinxes on Adam's bridge at Compton Verney, Warwickshire of c. 1760-65. See C. Hussey, English Country Houses, Mid Georgian 1760-1800, London, 1952, fig. 2.
